column1: 301055;instagram;2018-10-11 02:35:17;FALSE;"1 year and 4 months ago i left an abusive relationship. the first man i trusted to date after him raped me.
i went back to my abusive relationship and opened up to him about my rape and he did the same to me
column2: word for word saying he needed to own me again.

column1: it wasn‚Äôt until a few weeks later i gathered enough strength to leave him.
today is #worldmentalhealthday and i feel with everything going on in the news it is important to speak up.

column2: my sister helped me start my journey with counseling and psychiatry.

column1: i never reported my rape to the police because i thought no one would believe me when it came down to my word against his.
a physical examination was recorded by a gynecologist and a separate report was taken by a therapist.
i can‚Äôt tell you how i managed to get out of bed everyday for work or to take care of my son during those days.
my ugly past still affects me
column2: but i fight to control my future. i have been diagnosed with ocd
column4: generalized anxiety and chronic depression. through medication and behavioral therapy i have worked with my psychiatrist and therapist to push forward. i now recognize that rape does not define me; it defines a rapist.

column1: i‚Äôm not ashamed to admit i needed and continue to require help.
although there will be some who feel like i‚Äôm sharing too much information
column2: i know there are others out there trying to get out of an abusive relationship. people going through a traumatic experience
column3: who truly believe there is no other way out and nothing to look forward to. i‚Äôm sharing this for you.

column1: my sincere hope is if you‚Äôre going through something and feel alone
column2: that you realize there is real
column5: affordable help out there. despite what you may believe at this point in time
column6: you deserve better regardless of your feelings of guilt and shame.

column1: all you have to do is take one step forward.

column1: i sat down on¬†this wotld¬†mental¬†health day to add my voice to all the others crying out right now
column2: to add my story to all the other stories. i say down to talk about a trauma that didn't happen long long ago¬†before #metoo¬†and has become ""safer"" to talk about as the scars have formed
column3: but one that happened this summer and is still raw.

column1: i was going to tell you in detail about how i was assaulted and why i didn't report. i was going to tell you about the reactions i got when i told our mutual friends. i was going to tell you what they did afterwards. i was going to tell you how it has negatively effected me every day in my personal life and how even my professional life has suffered.
that may be what i sat down to do
column2: but it‚Äôs not what i‚Äôm doing anymore. ¬†i don't owe anyone my story
column4: my pain. but don't you dare think for just one moment that this isn't happening every day
column5: maybe even to someone you know
column6: maybe while you are just yards away. and here's the kicker... you may never know. ¬†let me say this one more time‚Ä¶ **you may never know.** it‚Äôs not just one type of person who assaults others and it‚Äôs not just one type of person who becomes a victim.

column3: & hurting. but i have a voice and i‚Äôm using it. telling you his name won‚Äôt change anything
column4: this isn‚Äôt about him. i am not trying to go through a social media trial because that won‚Äôt undo what has been done. but if you know who this is
column5: you can tell them that this was not okay this will not be tolerated. and you can make it clear to those around you that they are safe with you through your actions - because the words really don‚Äôt mean much without them.

;hot news aamir khan telah didukung untuk keluar dari proyek mogul karena subhash kapoor üòØ sepei yang diharapkan , aamir khan tidak melakukan apa pun yang jauh dari kesempurnaan . ketika dia ditanya tentang kontroversi tanushree dutta-a patekar selama peluncuran trailer film barunya , `` thugs hindostan '' , aamir , tanpa memihak dengan sungguh-sungguh mengatakan bahwa jika insiden sepei itu terjadi , maka itu harus diselidiki dengan benar . ketika gerakan semakin kuat dan cerita-cerita horor para korban muncul , menuduh para seleb populer sepei alok nath dan abhijeet bhattacharya dari perilaku seksual yang salah , aamir khan dan kiran rao mengadakan peemuan dengan producer guild . kemarin aamir mengeluarkan sebuah catatan yang menunjukkan solidaritasnya terhadap gerakan yang sedang berlangsung saat ini , sambil menegaskan pendiriannya bahwa ia tidak akan bekerja dengan orang-orang yang dituduh melakukan kejahatan semacam itu . satu bagian dari catatan aamir khan yang menarik perhatian publik yakni , `` dua minggu yang lalu , ketika kisah traumatis mulai bermunculan , kami mendapat perhatian bahwa seseorang yang akan mulai bekerja dengan kami telah dituduh melakukan pelanggaran seksual . setelah diselidiki , kami menemukan bahwa kasus khusus ini adalah subjudice , dan bahwa proses hukum sedang bergerak . kami bukan agen investigasi , kami juga tidak dalam posisi untuk menjatuhkan penilaian pada siapa pun yaitu untuk polisi dan pengadilan untuk melakukan . jadi , tanpa casting apapun aspersions pada siapa pun yang terlibat dalam kasus ini , dan tanpa membuat kesimpulan tentang tuduhan spesifik ini , kami telah memutuskan untuk menjauh dari film ini '' jadi film apa yang aamir khan bicarakan ? aamir belum secara resmi mengumumkan proyek apa pun yang ia bintangi setelah `` thugs hindostan '' . namun , ia terlibat dalam memproduksi film lain yang mungkin ia bintangin mogul . film ini adalah film biografi yang didasarkan pada kehidupan ayah bhushan kumar dan pendiri t-series , gulshan kumar . mogul akan diarahkan oleh subhash kapoor dari ketenaran seri film.. column4: jupiter moved into the sign of scorpio. that was the week the nytimes & new yorker published their investigative reports on harvey weinstein. soon after the #metoo movement seeded and quickly sprouted. so much has happened since
column5: the intensity and pace can overwhelm as well as awe.

column1: we also can feel that change isn‚Äôt fast enough
column2: and that any steps forward can be erased. the kavanaugh confirmation can feel like one such erasure. we could conclude we haven‚Äôt changed
column3: but the truth is we are not personally nor collectively the same. even if it feels at moments like we‚Äôve fallen back & down
column4: are still caterpillars ‚Äî we are not who we were. and we need to commit to our new selves.

column1: scorpio brings up what is hidden in our innermost parts and doesn‚Äôt do it in a pretty way (which venus
column3: would prefer) ‚Äî it just wants it all out. the ugliness. the truth. this dive to the core
column9: evolution can take place. what is trust or truth or values if underneath there are lies?

column2: emotionally charged time it can be hard to see the larger picture(s). our emotions may want us to be healed
column4: gone with the past now. the reality is what is being exposed and dug up has been around for a very long time
column5: woven into our social structures and institutions (capricorn). it takes time. have patience and keep persisting forward. find the signs that you and we are not the same. it is timely that there are a record number of women running for office and the nov 6th mid-term elections is lighting up our public interest as if it were a presidential election year. believe in yourself
column9: commit to who you are now.

column1: 301095;instagram;2018-10-10 19:37:52;FALSE;it took me a lot of time and courage to write this and express my thoughts to you all. it's definitely not easy being vulnerable in such an open platform
column2: but i wanted to address it as it is so important to me and many others who are in need of help. today i want to shed light on a topic that is not often discussed everywhere especially within the brown community. child sexual abuse or child molestation. as sad as the numbers are
column3: it has happened to many of us. you would think as you grew older
column4: you'll forget what happened because it took place when you were so small. whom are we kidding? it's impossible to forget. even more impossible when you're aware your molester(s) are walking around freely when they should be held accountable for their actions and given serious punishment. growing up with this pain
column7: faced major trust issues and anxiety every day. some days were just okay but most days felt like i couldn't go on. i was stuck in a really dark place and i blamed myself for everything that happened. i was too embarrassed to talk about it until i hit sixteen. when i heard about similar experiences
column8: it gave me the hope to talk about my story and tell my loved ones who helped me move on. nothing happened overnight
column10: but it finally felt possible to see the light and keep going. i reflected on my traumatic experiences and grew tough. i kicked the negative voices out of my mind and pushed myself to stop feeling guilty. when i look in the mirror today
column13: confident woman who didn't let her past affect her daily lifestyle anymore. i am so proud of the person i am today because i've really fought to become just me. and so can you. if you were a victim of child molestation
column14: you're not alone and you don't have to struggle with this on your own. it's critical to speak up and seek help
column17: or your friends. i am fortunate enough to have the best support system by my side and you also deserve the same love and support. your mental health is important at every stage of life
column18: from childhood and adolescence through adulthood. #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #notashamed;;en;#mentalhealthawareness

column1: 301113;instagram;2018-10-11 01:36:16;FALSE;"three years ago i had just finished my first year as a trainee when i was diagnosed with ptsd. you can say that the one thing that broke me
column2: put me back together again. ballet over these last few years has become cathartic. i went from never thinking i would step foot in a studio again

column2: 2018 a man attempted to sexually assault me while in an elevator. i survived and went without physical injury. mentally i was shook. i was engulfed in fear
column4: and anger. why? not just because his audacity to attempt
column5: but because this was not my first encounter with a sexual predator. from age 5-11 i was molested. at age 11 and 15 i was raped
column6: so at 25 being faced again with the monster that seemed to follow in different bodies momentarily froze me.

column2: i share this post to begin to take my voice back. to speak out and say sexual predators are wrong and no one deserves it
column4: or should be silent about it. though the justice system may fail us at times
column5: we are not alone. if anyone ever needs a friend to listen i'm here and one step at a time we will get our voice back. #metoo #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealthawarenessday #reauxzbrown #scarrednotflawed";;en;#MeToo

column3: vulnerable. i felt afraid for what ppl would think of me.

column2: it seems like the world is really becoming a different place. a place that accepts that mental health is important and that everyone is some level of ‚Äúcrazy‚Äù for lack of a better word. there have been times in the past couple years that i have felt perfectly accepting of having to live with a mental illness.

column1: it is not so weird after all

column2: i talk to someone who takes me back to the stigma i grew up with- and i do not know if the world is becoming more aware
column3: or if i have just replaced the ppl around me with more aware and empathetic ones.

and then as we got older it was upheld among our peers. some of our best friends snickered at our sadness.
this is not to blame them
column2: though. it was a little different

column1: 301198;instagram;2018-10-11 00:46:21;TRUE;;"we signed @glennondoyle's awesome love letter (who‚Äôs going to join me? i hope you all!) and my 2 girls & i wrote our own hand written/hand drawn letters. together we rise. together we can do anything. ‚†Ä

@glennondoyle millions of us spent last week imagining how it might feel to be dr. ford in this moment -- watching the aftermath of her world-shifting testimony unfold in this country. some warrior friends and i decided we must to do everything in our power to make sure dr. ford understands what her courage means to all of us. we need to make sure she hears -- directly from us -- that her heroic sacrifice was not in vain.‚†Ä
we know that while we fight against fear and hate and lies and greed- it is ever important to remember to actively love: to stop and honor those who stand mightily for hope

column2: we wrote dr. ford a love letter. our dream is that by the time dr. ford receives this letter
column3: she and her family will see that it‚Äôs been signed by every love warrior on earth. please take a moment
column5: to sit and read this letter. and then
column7: please sign your name. after the letter had made its way around the world
column8: we‚Äôll get it to dr. blasey ford.‚†Ä

column1: 301244;instagram;2018-10-10 22:41:52;FALSE;"‚Äúyou know what‚Äôs a slap in the face? the young men and women who bring the hard evidence to the table and still nothing is done. y‚Äôall want statistics on this? well check this out.
‚Ä¢1 in 5 women and 1 in 71 men will be raped at some point in their lives.
‚Ä¢in this ‚Äúgreat country‚Äù 1 in 3 women and 1 in 6 men experience some kind of contact sexual violence in their life.
‚Ä¢91% of rape/sexual assault victims are women and 9% are men.
‚Ä¢49.5% of multiracial women and 45% of indigenous/native were subjected to sexual violence in their life.
‚Ä¢8 out of 10 cases the victim knew the perpetrator(s)

‚Ä¢20% - 25% of college women and 15% of college men are victims of forced sex during their time in college ‚Ä¢a 2002 study revealed that 63.3% of men at one university who self-reported acts qualifying as rape or attempted rape admitted to committing repeat rapes ‚Ä¢ over 90% of sexual assault victims on college campuses do not report the assault ‚Ä¢27% of college women have experienced some form of unwanted sexual contact ‚Ä¢almost 2/3 of college students experience sexual harassment ‚Ä¢1-4 girls and 1-6 boys will he sexually abused before they turn 18
‚Ä¢30% of women were between the ages of 11 & 17 of their first completed rape.
‚Ä¢27.8% of men were age 10 or younger at the time of their first completed rape victimization
‚Ä¢more than 1/3 of women who report being raped before age 18 also experience rape as an adult ‚Ä¢between 2%-10% assault claims are false.

column1: 301258;instagram;2018-10-10 23:51:00;FALSE;"happy world mental health day. here goes: i am 23. i have had an anxiety disorder as long as i can remember
column2: lets say age 6/7? i have battled depression on and off since i was 15. i am a survivor. i am resilient. i try not to let my own mental health struggles get the best of me
column3: but sometimes they just do. thats how it is some days. those days i need a little extra support from those close to me. i do not let my mental illnesses define me. i am not anxiety or depression
column4: i am someone who happens to have it. i am beyond blessed for my therapist
column5: and my closest supports every single day. i love musical theatre
column6: i am in a master‚Äôs program to become a therapist myself and help others
column8: i am an aunt to 3 amazing kids
column9: i love my dog. but most importantly? i refuse to stop fighting. being a survivor
column10: having anxiety and depression: it can seem like you are 100% ok on the outside
column11: its an invisible illness at times
column12: but it isn‚Äôt invisible to me or my family. so here are a few things: whomever you are
column15: i too have a hard time feeling seen
column16: you are not alone. it is ok to not be ok sometimes. self care is the holy grail of importance. you are loved and you matter. you are worth love and acceptance. you are worth it all. happy world mental health day

column1: 301268;instagram;2018-10-10 23:54:47;FALSE;"love this... teacher liz kleinrock has used america's heated discourse on sexual violence as the springboard for lessons on consent for her third graders.
kleinrock says her consent lessons aren't about sex
column2: and that the concept of consent starts long before sexual relationships come into the picture.

column1: some people may feel weird about addressing consent with kids so young. but kleinrock says there are foundational lessons that need to start early
column2: which aren't directly tied to sex.

column1: @regran_ed from @teachandtransform -  everything about kavanaugh in the news has been making me heated. so whenever i get frustrated about the state of our country
column2: it inspires me to proactively teach my kids to do better. today was all about consent. we even explored the grey areas

column3: only a select few knew the severity of my illness. that‚Äôs the thing about having a stigma around mental illnesses

column4: lack there of) that caused me to

column1: 301330;instagram;2018-10-10 22:58:43;FALSE;"today is a bittersweet day. it marks what would have been my last day on my first ship in the military. today was the day i was to say goodbye to beautiful memories of bonding

column1: if you've followed me long enough
column2: you'll likely have heard about how i had to stand next to males who ostracized a woman for blowing the whistle on one of them for sexual #harrassment and sexual #assault. last week
column4: frankly) was pushed into the highest court in the country by men (and women) who ostracized a woman for sharing her story that that male sexually assaulted her and prioritized #politics over #humanity. he was pushed into a position of ultimate authority over women's rights by a male who
column5: himself was accused of sexual assault
column6: a male who called the accusers ""evil.""

column2: one of the males from the ship #complicit in the protection of the accused
column3: complicit in the ostracizing and psychological damage of the woman who blew the whistle
column4: was honored with a promotion. i left the ship because i'd lost faith that justice would ever be served by those with an interest to protect their own. i left because in good conscience
column5: i could not pretend none of it was wrong.

column2: today i also ran into my old chaplain (ship's religious pastor) from that ship. he was the one who helped me through my spiritual and emotional battle and i am forever indebted to him. but he told me today that had to leave the ship too. his fight with prostate cancer left him unable to continue serving on board. before he left
column3: he wished me well and said ""keep fighting for what you believe in. fight until there's nothing left to fight for and then fight to keep it that way.""

column3: and know what i want in this life. i am working my way towards it.

301372;instagram;2018-10-10 22:35:55;FALSE;"on world mental health day i felt like sharing the most important book i have read on the topic that empowered me to change by @officialdrjoedispenza . i have been through quite a few traumatic experiences but have used the meditations provided by the book to create a new reality and think new and different thoughts. it's not one hundred percent perfect but i feel like i have made a lot of progress and this book has been so critical
i actually was at the bookstore to get a different book that day but this one stood out to me and i changed my mind...i was so intrigued by the title
i was in treatment in santa monica at the time and feeling lost. rehab and addiction are very confusing and i was searching for answers to why i kept repeating the same mistakes
this book changed everything for me and i finally understood why i kept returning to the negative patterns and how to break the cycle
i ended up writing a paper on the book and now my therapist uses it in his groups.  obviously i am a major nerd
column2: i was the only one in treatment submitting papers but that's just who i am. i have always been a curious person who loves to read and write and actually enjoyed the process of writing it. if you want me to email you it dm me! it's a brief explanation of the book. occasionally i have reached out to my therapist when i have struggled since getting home and he tells me to re-read what i wrote and it helps me üíì

column1: 301427;instagram;2018-10-10 21:58:04;FALSE;"when you don‚Äôt dwell in your past but your past haunts you. the deep pain
column2: grief and fear hovers over you. the anxiety and exhaustion from being constantly on alert for danger is like a shadow following you wherever you go. you can try to run from it by numbing yourself out with your drug of choice
column3: but you can‚Äôt hide. there is no amount of time or magic words someone can say to make it disappear. you learn to live with it. you learn coping skills to prepare for the unexpected flashbacks
column4: nightmares and panic attacks. you can‚Äôt stop them but you can refuse to stay with them in the darkness. this is complex ptsd. ~

column1: we of harlan's emporium are two women who became friends in college and grew into sisters.
we have lived together for over 10 years
column2: struggled with #depression #anxiety and #adultadhd but that doesn't define us. we are introverts working in #academia and as #entrepreneurs .

column1: we are #millennials : in our household of three adults
column5: we have lived in low income housing. we try to balance our weekday jobs with our business and family. as three adults in one house
column6: looking after one baby. we have friends who are parents
column9: go to college... as exhausted as i feel
column10: i can't imagine how they do it. (shout out to @captktz @freespirited15

column1: we are #americanwomen who have had our own #metoo experiences; we are appalled by #systemicracism #rapeculture #toxicmasculinity and what the current administration is doing. daily. it's a nearly overwhelming wave - babies like ours
column2: denied health care because they are poor. families fleeing war and violence torn apart; babies like ours suffering mental and emotional torture in cages and tents
column3: in a system that was never designed to #reunitethem

column1: i ask myself why we have to #endthestigma when all of the individuals i know are dealing with #mentalheath issues of their own or a direct relationship. iowa
column3: cut funding for mental health when the needs are only growing. when the states biggest provider of mental health care is a literal prison. when we need to be #compassionate and understanding yet fight for all we are worth for the rights of those who are being oppressed in a way that unifies us against the actual oppressors not each other.... when people struggle daily with immediate needs so much that they can't worry about tomorrow

column1: this baby's laugh is life for me.
i have to hang onto that and keep striving for a better future.

column2: in the privacy of my car üòÇ).

column1: 301587;instagram;2018-10-10 20:24:38;FALSE;"@lynzylab wrote a powerful and funny song about the idea that this is a scary time to be a man. i highly recommend listening to it. i commented on her youtube video
column2: as you see here. i was quickly told that i needn't worry because there was zero chance of my being sexually assaulted. while i know perfectly well why he said that
column3: i tried to get him to say it (as of now he hasn't replied). but it's because no one wants to have sex with a willing fat woman
since fat girls and women absolutely get raped
column4: harassed and otherwise assaulted. but as hard as it is for a conventionally attractive women to be believed
column5: it's even worse for fat women. we're told to ""appreciate"" unwanted comments or behaviors from men because we should just be lucky anyone wants us at all

column1: umm fuck that shit. whether or not *you* find a woman attractive has nothing to do with whether or not another person has sexually assaulted her! it's crazy that in 2018 this even needs to be said. but clearly it does. thin privilege means that you're more likely to be believed if you're assaulted.  it shouldn't mean that
column2: and let me be crystal fucking clear by saying that even thin women aren't believed or given justice nearly enough.
i was never raped. but i've been otherwise assaulted and harassed
column3: and plenty of fat women *have* been the victims of rape.

column1: nothing i said came even close to warranting this comment (not that anything would justify it
column2: for the record). all i did was comment that i loved lynzy's song

column1: 301605;instagram;2018-10-10 17:00:36;FALSE;"today i've spent the day in bed because i didn't want to face the world
column2: i haven't had a wash or brushed my teeth
column3: i've looked in the mirror and hated what i have seen. there's a million things i've wanter to do but i just can't get my legs to take me there
column4: my brain is telling me i can't do this. i can't go and meet new people
column5: i can't do anything i want to do because i am not good enough for any of it. no one will like me anyway.

column1: there's plenty of things for me to do and dam i know i should be capable of doing them. i know there's a confident
column3: determined and strong ass girl inside of me that's screaming to be let out
column4: to be given the chance to grow and learn again just as she did many many years ago. i knew i who i was and i felt good about me and my ability to do things back then. i felt invincible and fearless. then something happened that eventually saw me crumble
column5: something that broke me to the core
column6: changed me as a person to the point i will never be who i once was and maybe that's ok
column7: it's time i really did make peace with that.

column2: i've had many days like this but i can't carry on this way
column3: i can't keep hurting the people i love and i can't keep hurting myself
column4: especially that little girl inside me who has had enough hurt and pain. i know what i need to do and how to allow her voice and passion flow into the world and i sure as hell know i've pushed her away and hurt her too many times. i've known i need to allow her to be free and do what she wants to do
column5: to feed the fire inside me that burns even if at times it's so small. i know it's always there.

column1: most of all i just want to belive in myself and my abilities again just like i did years ago. so when i feel like a faliure and that i can't carry on i know i have to for the girl inside me who needs me to carry on
column3: let her grow and most of all let her be loved. i don't really know what made me write this post & be so open tonight. but i have and there it is.

column1: 301626;instagram;2018-10-10 20:02:42;FALSE;"the last few weeks have left me in complete disbelief and shaking my head at the people who are supposed to be leading our country
column2: men and women. as a woman who is a survivor of multiple incidents of sexual misconduct
column3: all of this feels all too personal. *

column1: there is a lot i could say about the recent events
column2: but most of it has been said. it's hurtful
column5: and so very sad. it's so many things and yes
column6: i am still thinking about it and will probably never stop thinking about it as i raise my teenage daughters and my sweet little son in this country.

column1: i believe in the power of standing guard at the portal of your mind
column2: having awareness of your thoughts and only inviting the productive
column3: creative thoughts that fuel your dreams and desires and service to others. *

column1: as the negative thoughts have come to knock on the gates of my mind this past week
column2: the questions that deflected the negative thoughts are this: ""what can you do
column3: jessica? how can you make the biggest impact in your own space
column4: for you and for your children? what are the things that will make the difference?"" *

column1: my answer is this: i must continue to live and stand in my personal power. i must continue to be aware of who i am and who i am becoming to become the best possible version of myself for myself and my children. i must live in this awareness of who i am and share it with the world. i must continue creating a life i love living and showing my children how to do the same. *

column2: when women live in their personal power and create lives in alignment with who they be
column3: they make a stand each day that shows we will not live under the thumb of any human or circumstance. *

column1: if there is anything we still have left after this last week
column2: it's our freedom to create any life we want and stand firm in our personal power!  the patriarchy in this country might still be mighty and intact
column3: but it does not define me

column1: 301628;instagram;2018-10-10 20:03:09;FALSE;"when it‚Äôs your rest day for your workout but you need to blow off some steam you better power up with the happy yellow juice!
it‚Äôs been a very emotional day & the old me would stress eat but i know better now.
now i turn on a challenging workout that makes me sweat out the frustration.
i choose to make healthy decisions for my body by sweating it out.

i want to show my children healthy ways to deal with stress & hard feelings.  that is the legacy i want to leave them.

in the left photo yeah i look like shit. my hairs a mess
column2: my eyebrows aren't all neat and filled in and i've tears pouring down my face. i don't really care that i looked like shit
column3: because what i was feeling was 100 times worse than how i looked. mental health conditions aren't glamorous. they're painful and it feels like üí©üí©. even mentioning anything got to do with mental health in the past seemed like the hardest thing to do
column4: never mind talking about my own. struggling with mental health was something i used to be so ashamed of. so ashamed to the point that i was so afraid of anyone knowing that i was struggling
column5: that it used to make me sick.

column1: although i think the stigma around mental health has improved.. it's definitely still very much present. i've struggled with anxiety and depression for most of my life. again something that i used to be so ashamed of that i tried to go through all of it on my own. i've gone through times in my life that were so hard
column2: i honestly believed i would not survive them and that's not an easy thing to say. its so easy to he able to share these posts or say we support #mentalhealthday
column3: but it means nothing if nothing is actually done. i'm not ashamed to say i have struggled with my mental health
column4: and i still do. it doesn't define me as a person. i've worked extremely hard to get where i am today and know there are millions of others that have too. so if you have a problem with mental health
column5: or decide to change your opinion of me or anyone else who is suffering just because of this post.. i've afraid that's your own issue
column6: not mine. and if you think someone might be struggling
column7: it really won't take much out of your day to ask if they're okay ‚ù§Ô∏è you got this üí™

column1: 301661;instagram;2018-10-10 19:41:47;FALSE;"i fought against the implications of this verse (as it related to my abuse) for a long time. i've always had a vision of god's will as two options weighed in either hand
column2: with god deciding which would outweigh the other
column3: the suffering or the redemption. in general terms
column4: that's a hard pill to swallow. in personal terms
column6: it was unbearable. once i fully accepted and spoke about the years of abuse i sustained
column7: the picture of god allowing it to happen to me seemed too cruel to even fathom. how could he? and yet he did. and yet i still believed in his existence
column8: and even his inherent goodness. but i wrestled inside for years. i withdrew from established church. i could not trust the institution or those inside it any longer. i pressed the bible for answers to only throw it down. i believed that the living word could and should stand up to any question you ask of it. i hated god

column2: something was happening. i thought that it was me that was walling myself off from others
column3: but it was god shutting me in and calling me out. he was calling out the girl that was hiding
column4: buried under years of shame and denial. he knew she would only come out if no one was around. with his hand grasping mine
column5: step by step we climbed. and with me came rage and so much shame. why didn't i ever fight? why didn't i tell? it must have been my weakness
column6: it must have been because i was a girl instead of a boy
column7: and it must have been because i didn't matter at all. i was nothing. it must be true
column8: and so i buried that lie so deep under years and years of shame. no one must know. and then out i came.

column1: and now i wear my story like a badge of honor. i never asked for it and i didn't want it
column3: standing on top of the mountain i was meant to be buried under. it is very important to me that women and men see this side of abuse. all i knew was what i saw. the hiding little girl
column4: who grows up to be the hiding woman. i am done hiding because i have nothing to hide.

column2: a mid aged man who lived with his wife
column3: came and stood in one such corner next to us. he got into a conversation with some of us and joined our group. .

column1: 301701;instagram;2018-10-10 19:19:40;FALSE;"it's sad to see men and more saddening seeing women supporting the new #himtoo movement because the aim of this movement is toxic and aimed to silence
column2: subject to ridicule the testimony of abused women with the intention of silencing them and causing uneccesary trauma to rape/sexual assault victims.

column1: the response of the son to his mum's tweet gave me hope that our effort are not in vain (swipe right to see it)

i'm not saying that there aren't girls or women who may have lied against innocent men and when caught they should be sentenced too and i also agree that every case must throughly be investigated but we all need to realize that the amount of women that lie against men are far less than the 1% of all the rape cases.

no one  should capitalize on that small percentage to silence and shame the millions of real victims of rape/sexual assault. this is so disgusting and upsetting. for men to even say that they can't no longer look or talk to a woman for fear of them accusing them is stupid
column2: childish and a ploy to stop the growing support for the victims. why not educate themselves and their sons that rape is wrong and there must be consequences for harassing/raping a woman why not learn and teach their sons to respect every woman. for centuries women
column4: children and even men and boys have been abused and we shouldn't allow anyone to discredit the powerful #metoo movement. it's important
column5: it's needed and we shouldn't stop fighting and speaking up. even if we don't get justice in every court case let's keep fighting and make sure we create a system where every victim gets justice. let make sure that rapists
column6: abusers etc. are made to face the consequences of they're action
column7: no matter when the abuse happened. i stand with every victim of rape and sexual assault and i will keep advocating for us. we are not victims

column1: my names elizabeth and i have anxiety
column2: ocd and depression. i went to therapy almost every week for four years. i take prozac to keep my demons drowsy. the skeletons in my closet have become friendly and my luggage i use to carry around has been set aflame by me. darkness is my old friend but now the moon shines brighter at night.

column1: i‚Äôm here to tell you it gets easier. it becomes fun again. you will laugh until your belly aches. tears will not fall as often. you are so strong and capable of overcoming this. whatever you deal with
column2: i am here for you. i am your life cheerleader. it‚Äôs easy to try to lift someone up but to lift yourself up and keep going is hard fucking work. i know. i have been there and i am here to remind you to keep pushing those boundaries.

column1: your problems and demons will never go away entirely
column2: but they do become easier to handle. mine are actually my friends now. it took a long time and every single day is and was an effort to keep moving forward but i did it and you can to.

column1: keep your head up. hug yourself. let yourself cry if you need to. sing that song so loud you almost throw up from strain. release those feelings and then accept them for what they are and then use them to your advantage. you are made of stardust and the stars shine in your eyes.";;en;;;;;;0;;midwestdreaming;Elizabeth;;0;False;11;0;0;45;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/f85736334ece6f7a40a7991e5b02e181/5D1B21D9/t51.2885-15/e35/42469374_1155604717937992_1496668191944829179_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"hey

column2: please be aware of the struggles your loved ones are fighting within closed doors on their own... being a mum of 2 angels and fighting it since 2016
column3: all i know is that it takes every fibre to keep your sanity when there's no one to help you fight with the darkness that takes over your mind and clouds your judgment and how you see things... the worse is when you are expecting and your doctor refuses to give you medication since you've never been on one... and then all you can do is fight it .. everyday.. on your own... i feel lucky for being aware of it
column4: and for asking help and most of all being blessed with a father who taught us to have strong will power b/c it was my will to defeat it and to make myself better for my family and the unborn... and yet i know there are many who are fighting it in silence
column5: struggling & at times being defeated by it... it is easy to tell someone fighting depression to come out and ask for help but trust me
column6: it isn't. .. it is really difficult to tell someone and ask their help... and to make matters worse

column1: this was a sketch i made a few months ago when something in my head was clouding my ability to think straight. i penned it down to express what i felt: it's a feeling where you are completely helpless about your present situation. every person around you thinks that you are fine. happy even. you tell them that you are too. sometimes you even use the word ""great"" to describe how you are. but you know you are not. if you say something
column2: you are afraid to be put inside an hourglass
column3: to be told to stay there until it's time that the world is safe for you. you fear you will lose all that you have. however hard you tried
column4: you fear that your family and friends
column5: who told you a billion times to be careful would think that you were not. you bottle it all up. and one day there is a movement
column6: and you speak with the hope to settle those butterflies in your gut for good. you write on. you say #metoo . and the whole world says ""why now?"" this sketch is to recognise the recent call outs on sexual abuse. victims are afraid. traumatised. they have taken this long to recover
column7: while some even continuing to be around offenders with a feeling of 'no choice'. i hold great respect for the movement and for the people taking to the streets of social media. this is at the very least
column8: urging people to realise that they are not alone
column9: and they do in fact have a choice.

column1: just to clarify sexual assaults apply to all genders. if you are not female and have been sexually assaulted by men/women
column2: you can speak up too! feminism is the advocacy of women's rights on the ground of equality of sexes
column3: and not about prejudiced support for women. and
column4: there is a difference between power and empowerment.

column1: what most of us don't realize
column2: is that every ounce of milk
column3: scoop of ice cream and bite of cheese comes at the expense of a mother and her child. by indulging in a seemingly harmless pleasure
